{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2bf5e897",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Accessing device properties without an IBM Quantum account\n",
    "\n",
    "```{post} 2023-05-12\n",
    ":author: Paul Nation\n",
    ":category: Hardware\n",
    ":tags: Hardware\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "db1abf95",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Background\n",
    "\n",
    "The properties of an IBM Quantum device (called a 'backend' in Qiskit) are important parameters used to gauge the qulity of a machine, provide additonal information for the circuit compilation process, and additional information needed for scheduling circuits and pulse-level control.  Most often this information is retrived directly from a backend object in Qiskit after loading your IBM Quantum account.  However, the properties of all the deployed devices on the [IBM Quantum website](https://quantum-computing.ibm.com/services/resources) are accessible with no account at all!  This is actually quite unique, as most quantum hardware vendors provide device-level details only to paying clients, or at most give a static snapshot at some instance of time.  Qiskit itself includes static snapshots of IBM Quantum devices that can be used for transpilation and noisy simulations.  However, because devices properties can vary over time, these \"fake backends\" are rarely a good model for a live system.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we show you how to query the IBM Quantum API directly for current system properties, and show how to utilize this information in a couple of different ways."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1bbb9658",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Fontmatter"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "97566f6e",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Package for querying the IBM Quantum API\n",
    "import requests\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "\n",
    "# Load all the basic Qiskit functionality\n",
    "from qiskit import *\n",
    "# Get the properties and configuarition classes used to define the data for a Qiskit backend\n",
    "from qiskit.providers.models import BackendProperties, QasmBackendConfiguration\n",
    "# The 'fake' Qiskit backend class\n",
    "from qiskit.providers.fake_provider import FakeBackend\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plotting routines\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "%config InlineBackend.figure_format='retina'\n",
    "try:\n",
    "    plt.style.use('quantum-light')\n",
    "except:\n",
    "    pass"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cf7fc9a1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Querying the IBM Quantum API\n",
    "\n",
    "The `requests` library can be used to query API points, such as those of IBM Quantum.  The URL of interest here is: `'https://api-qcon.quantum-computing.ibm.com/api/Backends/BACKEND_NAME/properties'`, where `BACKEND_NAME` is the name of the target system.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the following example, I will target the `ibm_seattle` device, our largest (433Q) deployed system, and use `requests.get()` to get the properties.  I have also added a check to the request here to make sure the returned data is valid as I kept mis-spelling backend names:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "ff21fa18",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "props_res = requests.get('https://api-qcon.quantum-computing.ibm.com/api/Backends/ibm_seattle/properties')\n",
    "if not props_res.json().get('backend_name', None): raise Exception('Request failed')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5625b5a3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, ideally we should convert the returned payload into something that we can utilize in Qiskit.  The `.json()` methjod of `props_res` returns a Python dictionary that can be directly converted into a `BackendProperties` object in Qiskit:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "ceac64f1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "props = BackendProperties.from_dict(props_res.json())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fe75660c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now that we have a properties object, we can use it to do things like plot device performance metrics or, with a bit of work (but it is worth it), generate a \"fake\" backend useful for transpiling circuits and running noisy simulations using the live calibration data that the properties represents."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6617a062",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Making a 'fake' backend from BackendProperties\n",
    "\n",
    "To make our lives even easier, it is beneficial to create a `FakeBackend` instance that we can directly use in the Qiskit `transpile` function and can be used for generating a noise model from the device and performing noisy simulations.\n",
    "\n",
    "So, it turns out that while you can query the properties of a IBM Quantum system without logging in, you cannot grab the configuration of the system.  The `configuration` represents static attributes of the backend, e.g. things like the backend name, Quantum Volume (if any), `rep_delay` time, etc.  The properties, contains things like gate and measurement errors, qubit frequencies, etc.; attributies of the quantum system and its components that can vary over different calibration cycles.\n",
    "\n",
    "The function below generates a `FakeBackend` object from the properties data obtained from the API call.  Here we use `FakeBackend` rather than the newer `FakeBackendV2` as the former is more inline with the backend objects returned from the Qiskit IBM provider."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "1dd39502",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def fake_backend_from_properties(props):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Return a FakeBackend from a BackendProperties object\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Parameters:\n",
    "        props (BackendProperties): A backend properties instance\n",
    "        \n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        FakeBackend: A fake backend matching the given properties data\n",
    "        \n",
    "    Raises:\n",
    "        ValueError: Could not determine the two-qubit basis gate type\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    # Generate the set of basis gates from the gate info in the properties\n",
    "    basis_gates = set()\n",
    "    for gate in props.gates:\n",
    "        basis_gates.add(gate.gate)\n",
    "    basis_gates = list(basis_gates)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Determine the two-qubit entangling gate used to generate the coupling map\n",
    "    two_qubit_gate = None\n",
    "    if 'cx' in basis_gates:\n",
    "        two_qubit_gate = 'cx'\n",
    "    elif 'ecr' in basis_gates:\n",
    "        two_qubit_gate = 'ecr'\n",
    "    elif 'cz' in basis_gates:\n",
    "        two_qubit_gate = 'cz'\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        raise ValueError('I do not know what 2Q gate the backend is using')\n",
    "    # Iterate over the two-qubit gates to obtain the coupling map\n",
    "    coupling_map = []\n",
    "    for gate in props.gates:\n",
    "        if gate.gate == two_qubit_gate:\n",
    "            coupling_map.append(gate.qubits)\n",
    "    # Form a configuration object from the data in the properties\n",
    "    config = QasmBackendConfiguration(backend_name=props.backend_name,\n",
    "                                      backend_version=props.backend_version,\n",
    "                                      n_qubits=len(props.qubits),\n",
    "                                      basis_gates=basis_gates,\n",
    "                                      gates=basis_gates, # This is not really valid, but not using it\n",
    "                                      local=True,\n",
    "                                      simulator=False,\n",
    "                                      conditional=True,\n",
    "                                      open_pulse=False,\n",
    "                                      memory=True,\n",
    "                                      max_shots=None,\n",
    "                                      coupling_map=coupling_map)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Overload the properties method on the FakeBackend to return our properties\n",
    "    def properties():\n",
    "        return props\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Form the actual FakeBackend to return \n",
    "    fake_backend = FakeBackend(config)\n",
    "    fake_backend.properties = properties\n",
    "\n",
    "    return fake_backend"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2cc8eebd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us now construct a fake backend corresponding to the live `ibm_seattle` system that we queried above:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "6c7b9ff9",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "fake_backend = fake_backend_from_properties(props)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c82b8d07",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Using our fake_backend"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f83c0d6a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Plotting backend parameters\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we will plot the two-qubit (ECR gates) for the backend:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "97f3d728",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1600x1200 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 1122,
       "width": 1484
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# The coupling map for the device\n",
    "coupling_map = fake_backend.configuration().coupling_map\n",
    "\n",
    "# Grab the ECR gate error for every edge in the coupling map\n",
    "data = [props.gate_error('ecr', edge) for edge in coupling_map]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Make a figure instance\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "# Plot the data as a density plot\n",
    "density = sns.kdeplot(data,ax=ax, log_scale=True, bw_adjust=1e-1, fill=True, alpha=0.8)\n",
    "# Set and remove labels\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('Two-qubit error rate')\n",
    "for ylabel in ax.get_yticklabels():\n",
    "    ylabel.set_visible(False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "08eb2362",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Transpiling and noisy simulation\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we will take a simple GHZ circuit, purposely designed to introduce swap gates, and transpile the circuit in a noise-aware manner that triggers [Mapomatic](https://doi.org/10.1103/PRXQuantum.4.010327).  We cannot however use the `ibm_seattle` device here.  This is because this system has `faulty_qubits`; qubits that are completely unoperational at the time.  This is a new concept, and one that is incomplatible with the noise model geneating functions within Qiskit Aer.  As such, we will use the `ibm_sherbrooke` device:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "c9f94397",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "props_res2 = requests.get('https://api-qcon.quantum-computing.ibm.com/api/Backends/ibm_sherbrooke/properties')\n",
    "if not props_res2.json().get('backend_name', None): raise Exception('Request failed')\n",
    "    \n",
    "props2 = BackendProperties.from_dict(props_res2.json())\n",
    "fake_backend2 = fake_backend_from_properties(props2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "38682f4b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Make a circuit with four, two-qubit gate connections on a single-qubit, thus requiring swap gates:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "id": "00d22e88",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "qc = QuantumCircuit(5)\n",
    "qc.h(0)\n",
    "qc.cx(0,1)\n",
    "qc.cx(0,2)\n",
    "qc.cx(0,3)\n",
    "qc.cx(0,4)\n",
    "qc.measure_all()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a2445f4e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Transpile the circuit to the fake backend:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "id": "c4796530",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 4563.33x2240.78 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 17,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 1875,
       "width": 3736
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "trans_qc = transpile(qc, fake_backend2, optimization_level=3)\n",
    "trans_qc.draw('mpl', idle_wires=False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c4ed48a6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Note that the noise aware transpiler components have mapped the circuit to what appears to be the optimal set of qubits at the time.\n",
    "\n",
    "We can now take the transpiled circuit and run it on our `fake_backend2` that will automatically generate a noise model and perform a noisy simulation of the circuit, modelling the live device noise. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "id": "6f0eef7e",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "{'10101': 1,\n",
       " '00001': 3,\n",
       " '01110': 4,\n",
       " '01101': 1,\n",
       " '10011': 2,\n",
       " '01111': 7,\n",
       " '01000': 17,\n",
       " '10001': 7,\n",
       " '11011': 6,\n",
       " '01001': 1,\n",
       " '11110': 7,\n",
       " '00110': 1,\n",
       " '11111': 450,\n",
       " '00100': 3,\n",
       " '01100': 1,\n",
       " '10111': 23,\n",
       " '10000': 2,\n",
       " '11001': 1,\n",
       " '11101': 16,\n",
       " '00010': 14,\n",
       " '00000': 433}"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 18,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fake_backend2.run(trans_qc, shots=1000).result().get_counts()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "efdf3a95",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can see that a noisy simulation was performed as bit-strings other than the ideal outcomes (`'11111'` and `'00000'`) are beiung returned."
   ]
  },
